 of philosophical anthropology and ritual studies.In the first section of the book Wittgenstein's remarks are presented and discussed in light of his Nachlass and relevant lecture-notes by G.E. Moore, reproduced in this book as facsimiles. The second section deals with the cultural and philosophical background of the early remarks, while the third section focuses specifically on the general problem of understanding as being a main issue of these remarks. The fourth section concentrates on the philosophical development characteristic of the later remarks. Finally, the fifth section reviews Wittgenstein's opposition to Frazer, and the ramifications of his remarks, in light of ritual studies.The book is intended for scholars in philosophy and religious studies, as well as for the general reader with an academic interest in philosophy and the philosophy of religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 4aFrazer, James George. 4aReligionsphilsophie. 4aWittgenstein, Ludwig. 4aphilosophy of religion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh1 aAlbinus, Lars, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRothhaupt, Josef G. F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSeery, Aidan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2016z9783110485301oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831104537200 cprintz978311045347840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311045506940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110455069423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110455069.jpg  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Pack